Me and my boyfriend have decided to have the small ceremony but not the legal paperwork. He probably would go through with the legality of it all if I truly wanted it…But I don’t. I want to live the life of a married couple. But what I don’t want is for us, specifically him to ever feel trapped into staying for fear of consequences outside of heartbreak. Meaning that if someday he wasn’t in love with me anymore, and didn’t want to put in the work to rekindle that love, I wouldn’t want him to stay for fear of losing his assets. As someone who loves him now, I want him to have the freedom to leave at any given time. And I just don’t think that the “incentives” in place rn make marriage by a legal contract worth it. It’s not a lack of commitment. If anything it shows more commitment to strive to make it work while also at the same time making it easier to leave.
If we were to ever “divorce” the biggest concern I’d want us to have is how we are gonna break the news to the other person. Not “Do I need to call my lawyer first?” Personally I think a lot of people, specifically men are being guilt tripped into feeling like they “have a fear of commitment”. When in reality it is more often a fear of what happens if you chose someone else who wasn’t ready to commit to you to the same capacity? comment_text:
My wife was diagnosed with M.S. in 1996. We got together in 2005, and I’ve been her full-time carer ever since. We married four years ago.

I studied Fine Art at Leeds College of Art & Design from 1997 to 2000. But truthfully? College didn’t teach me shit. 99% of what I know, I taught myself. From my teens onward I was learning on my own time - pulling things apart, experimenting, getting better because I wanted to, not because someone told me to. The grades were great, sure - but that wasn’t because of what they gave me. It was what I already had in me before I even walked through the door.

I couldn’t build a normal career - I couldn’t go out to work because my wife’s needs came first. Freelance never lined up with reality. Eventually we ended up stuck - financially, emotionally, mentally. Just trying to get through the days. Fifteen years disappeared like that. Survival mode. Looping.

Then in 2021 I discovered NFTs - and for the first time, I saw a way I could build something on my terms. From home. Around her care.
I have an intelligent, pattern-recognising mind. I’ve spent my life studying all kinds of subjects in my own time - art, culture, psychology, systems, design, consciousness, strategy. I absorb everything. And when NFTs showed up, I didn’t just skim the surface - I pulled the whole thing apart.

So I didn’t just learn crypto - I studied the entire space. I figured out what works. What lasts. What doesn’t. What every single project was missing, no matter how hyped. And why most fail.

So I started building. And I’ve spent the last 14 months creating the biggest thing I’ve ever made: Hopium Town.
It’s disgusting and weird. It’s beautiful and manic. It’s hand-drawn - somewhere over 3,000+ parts, no AI, no generators. It’s held together with an invisible design structure most people will never notice. And under the chaos? It’s real. It’s made with love. It’s built from pain. It’s layered with hope.

It’ll be ready around the end of June 🚀

And because it’s a story-driven series of projects, Hopium Town is only the beginning.
There are at least 3 more major projects coming - each one smaller, rarer, more intense - and 3 or more side projects and more.
The whole thing forms a long story arc - a strange, playful, emotionally charged narrative that spans years, formats, and ideas. It’s built to evolve, and every part of it connects.

But this isn’t just a project.
With the funds from this project, I'll be helping my wife fight M.S. and I’m building a business - working toward something much bigger. It’s built on the concept of Hopium, with a structure designed to create value, help people, and change the world.

I have a mission: To unfuck the world, and make it unfuckable.

And underneath it all - I’m a Psychedelic Innovator.
Ever since I first dropped acid in 1998, ideas have never stopped pouring into me. Not shallow thoughts - systems. Visions. Massive, layered concepts I call "Blueprints from the Ether". I don't know where they come from, but I’ve been receiving them for 27 years. And now, finally, I’m building the kind of business that can bring those ideas into the real world. I'll be hiring the minds needed to construct the wildest, most beautiful versions of the future I’ve carried for decades. AI Agents alone wont manage what I have planned.

This isn’t a quick flip or a fantasy moonshot.
It’s the first major thing I’ve truly finished in my life - and the start of something with no ceiling.
I’m not here to sell hype.
I’ve waited half my life to build this.

video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
While it is true that some avoidants were ignored and learned to self-soothe, that is very rare, and it is not the primary way people become avoidants. 

Most avoidants were enmeshed with and used emotionally by one or both caregivers. For instance, a single parent makes their child a surrogate spouse. They share too much adult information with the child and rely on their child to meet their emotional needs. This happens often in a divorce. In other cases, a parent might be sick or have addiction issues, which places the child in the emotional caregiving role. The helicopter mother or father. The possibilities are endless. The common denominator is that a parent places their emotional stability and emotional needs in the hands of the child. 

Think of it this way. The umbilical cord is meant to feed and nourish the child. WIth avoidants, the umbilical cord is flipped and the parent sucks the emotional life out of the child to feed themselves. Therefore, as an adult, when their partner makes a request or attempt for intimacy and connection, they will run. They relive the unhealed pain, frustration, and anxiety they experienced for having to take care of their parent/s. 

Their most effective strategy to avoid repeating the engulfment they experienced as a child is to continuously pursue what is called outside intensity. This means they always have something going on that is more important than the relationship. It can be their career, hobbies, the gym, pets, their children, becoming sick, addictions, affairs... It is a brilliant strategy because, in most cases, they can easily defend how they are deceptively avoiding connection and intimacy. It is hard to argue with a hard worker or a parent who spends time with the kids, is sick, loves their pet, or has a hobby, and it allows them to blame their partner for being too needy.

The blaming of their partner is how they discharge the unhealed pain, shame, and anger that they feel for being enmeshed with, engulfed, and ultimately abandoned by their parent. Fascinatingly, while it would seem like they were treated specially because the parent paid so much attention to them and gave them so much emotional power over them, ultimately, since they are using the child emotionally, they have also completely abandoned the child. 

That is why when their partner stops pursuing attachment, intimacy, and connection with them and withdraws, the avoidant comes running back.

So, the avoidant's conscious fear is intimacy and connection. They "think" they want to pursue other things much more than the relationship, and that those pursuits fulfill them. They are out of touch with the reality of what is really driving their outside intensity desires. 

Their subconscious fear is abandonment. They are entirely unaware that they were used and abandoned emotionally as a child, and that those outside pursuits are an attempt to medicate away their pain. They are unaware they are using their careers, hobbies, the gym, the kids, pets, illness, and all of their outside intensity pursuits to avoid the deep, unhealed pain from their childhood. 

In reality, deep down, they hunger for intimacy and connection, and they won't get into that truth and reality until they address the unhealed enmeshment pain from their childhood. Once they do, their desire for their outside intensity pursuits will become mature and moderate instead of all-consuming.

video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
First of all, great conversation provided by @thediaryofaceo 

26:54: Paul Brunson’s statement, “We have to lower our expectations of our partners,” is an important idea to reflect on. As a society, we are often taught to expect our partner to be our one and only—the sole person we rely on emotionally, socially, and intellectually. In my country, there’s even a saying: one shouldn’t put the spoon between husband and wife, meaning people shouldn’t interfere in a marriage. While this saying dates back to ancient times, there was a strong sense of community up until 40–50 years ago.

For example, if my mother needed something, she would call my grandmother, her sisters or sisters-in-law, or her uncle. There were certain issues she never discussed with my father simply because he wouldn’t understand them—just as there were things my father never discussed with her. This reflects a time when people didn’t expect their spouse to fulfill every need—support came from different sources. Even now, as an adult, there are topics I don’t discuss with my mother, others I don’t discuss with my father, and some conversations I can have with both of them separately, one-on-one. And I am sure they don't rely on me or everything they need.

I feel that nowadays we make less effort to maintain a connection with a broader community. We don’t engage in daily conversations with like-minded people as much as before - we don't even speak to our neighbours anymore - and as a result, we subconsciously place all our expectations onto our partners, because they are the only intimate relation we maintain on a daily basis. When Paul Brunson talks about lowering our expectations, he isn’t suggesting that we settle for less. Rather, he means we should stop expecting one person to provide everything for us. Instead, we should seek fulfillment from multiple people in our lives. When we stop looking for "the perfect partner" and start looking for someone who has similar milestones and has some level of compatibility with oneself then we can build a fulfilling relationship. 

Ultimately, if we choose to, we can learn to tolerate and respect others. This is why some arranged marriages succeed—not necessarily because of deep compatibility, but because both partners consciously (or subconsciously) agree to make it work and respect one another for the sake of a lifelong partnership.

Hello Steven. I love these podcasts, seen almost all of them. Really appreciate the time you, your team and the guest speakers put into it. 

I’m watching the one on attraction now. It’s valentines day, so I considered sharing to my social media. video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
Listening to what you were saying, I reflected on how everything in life has a beginning and an end, and there are always parts that are difficult and parts that are easy. There’s a saying about whether to do the hard things first or the easy things first, and the logical approach is to tackle the hard things first.

But when it comes to marriage, we do the exact opposite. Getting married is extremely easy—there are no requirements, no training, no preparation—while getting out of a marriage is incredibly difficult. By the time people realize they need to leave, they are already drained, and the process of divorce—court battles, family interference, and emotional exhaustion—becomes overwhelming. That’s why more people today are choosing to stay single or live together without marriage.

If we applied the “hard things first” approach, marriage would require real preparation. There should be courses and certifications in anger management, communication, and relationship skills before people are allowed to marry. This would have two major benefits. First, it would reduce problems because couples would be better prepared for challenges. Second, if issues did arise, people would be more willing to reflect, be patient, and try to fix things rather than give up easily—because they had already put in significant effort.

And if, despite all that, divorce was still necessary, it should be an easy process. Right now, we’re doing things backwards: marriage is too easy to enter, and leaving is too difficult.

Also, making marriage slightly harder to obtain would actually make it more attractive. People tend to value what is difficult to get, and if marriage required effort and preparation, it would become something people truly work for rather than something they rush into. Of course, we shouldn’t push it to the point where people become obsessed with the idea of marriage just because it’s hard to get. But adding some level of challenge would make people more serious about it, leading to stronger, more thoughtful commitments.

If we reversed the way marriage works—making it something people must truly prepare for while ensuring that leaving is not a nightmare—relationships would be healthier, and society would be more stable.

comment_text:
My husband and I have been married for 40 years, best decision we ever made, we are best mates, lovers and partners. We have three adults sons, all of whom want to marry, one already has...the reason my husband and I wanted to marry is for children, we wanted our family to have the same surname, a sense of unity, a sense of 'us'  a solidness- it's hard to describe, but to children I wonder if they feel that if their parents aren't married they aren't thinking 'are they looking for an easy way out' or 'how solid is the relationship or commitment?' maybe they don't know any different as it is what they are used to and I don't know how people think today but that is how I felt back in the 80s. The world is changing so fast but I would still want to marry today. I am guessing it is no guarantee of staying together anymore, the problem I think is the lead up to marriage and the work people put in to the relationship and looking ahead and foreseeing possible bumps and how they can over come them. You don't invest in a huge life change without doing your homework, why should marriage be any different? Discuss, the future, what does the other person want out of life, how well can you overcome a disagreement etc. all part of the analysis everyone should do, not romantic, but if that is the only reason you are marrying....don't do it.
I always looked at a potential partner this way....how does he treat a waiter? How does he speak to his parents, how is he with children, how is he with animals. All of those are deal breakers to me if they don't have respect, we have disagreements, but never if 40 years have we called each other names or sworn at each other. Total respect. We stick to the subject we are disagreeing on and talk frankly. We also laugh a lot...magic ingredient.

I disagree with the Racism Within Dating bit. It has been scientifically proven humans of all races prioritize looks above all else and there are distinct physical differences between races - that's the only non-malicious reason for racial categorization to even exist. If certain races have facial features that are on average less attractive to the majority of potential partners, that will display in the dating world. Racism implies hatred/fear generated from outside sources, whereas attraction comes from a place we can't influence or change as far as I know. In the same way a gay person can't find opposite sex atractive, how is it any different for racial preferences?

It's uncomfortable and challenges the ideal that humans are all equal in all ways, but there are many intrinsic inequalities as parts of our daily lives. Rich have unequally better and longer lives compared to poor people. People with high IQ lead unequally more fulfilling and happier lives than less intelligent people. Is it that much of a stretch to assume race having the same unfair, inherit inequalities tied to it?

If it can't be changed, if it is a natural tendency and not a human invention, history has proven many times it is best for everyone to form a belief system that incorporates the truth, no matter how difficult it may be, while minimizing the inevitable negative outcomes such as feelings of superiority based on these intrinsic advantages. You wouldn't consider yourself superior to a person of same age in a wheelchair, nor necessarily treat them with pitty, despite being undisputably physically more able. video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
I found this episode very interesting. I didn’t agree on everything. There are a few points I want to make: 

1) keeping secrets is different from understanding when it’s better to share a certain information with your partner and temporary holding on talking about it. I don’t agree on keeping secrets which by definition means you know you’re hiding something relevant that you should say and you don’t, and having some basic communication understanding and knowing you shouldn’t probably start to talk about the toothpaste issue that annoys you at your partner’s dad funeral!
The example that Paul made about not telling that the ex wrote him because he knew that his partner was having some jealousy issues is exactly the opposite of what may help the relationship to grow. You have the opportunity to demonstrate that your partner can trust you by sharing that information that you know she would like to be informed about. You can show her the message and demonstrate that nothing bad happened by answering to that message. What happens instead if your partner finds out the message one day? Her jealousy will increase because she’ll start to wonder why you hide that message. 

2) apologising is different from feeling sorry. I think it’s important to always say that you feel sorry for how your partner felt for a certain behaviour that you may have had. This doesn’t mean that you wouldn’t do it again, it means you acknowledge their feelings and you are sorry for them to feel hurt or sad or whatever. Saying this to your partner can then open the conversation about why they felt in that way and you can work on it together. Even agree that in future you would behave in the same way but because this was discussed, your partner may not feel bad in front of the same situation basically.

3) NEVER going to sleep angry. This has been my rule number 1 since the beginning of my relationship. It’s true that you have the opportunity to process better after sleep however the morning after you may think it wasn’t important enough and let it go (really bad! Because this will make things accumulate!). You may also start to overthink when arguments are not soon resolved. It may be my personal experience - even though I think this happens to at least many women too - as a defence mechanism when I feel hurt I start to make the person that made me feel hurt my enemy. It’s a toxic way of thinking about the other person that pushes me to get apart, run away and say “fuck off, I don’t care about this person”. The longest I wait to solve the conflict, the worst this becomes. So my solution is to talk as soon as possible and what is really helpful is a kind reminder from my partner that he loves me and we’re on the same boat. That helps stop my toxic thoughts. Try this guys! 😂


Having said this, I love the discussion on these topics! It always makes me think on how I can improve my happy relationship! 
Thank you for your job Steven!

comment_text:
Not so cut and dry. Can't ignore any correlations of how divorces happen even when nobody is sick. The same pushing away, the same blame game, the same alienations can happen when a wife is sick as when nobody is sick.
The death of a child is a hard precursor for a relationship ending because there's a severe strain put on the relationship because the wife see things as she lost a child, not as they lost a child.
So the husband isn't allowed to grieve the same way. It changes the dynamics of the relationship. And ultimately things fall apart. So it's not just "the man just leaves" like everybody wants to paint it out to be.
The burden of performance that men have is add odds with the support and the grieving that they are also going through.
It's a very bad mix of having to still provide, being accused of not emotionally supporting if they take a "try to fix things" approach, then get into a competitive dynamic of "you're not the one that's dying..." if they show any signs of grieving. And that point contains it's own "not being seen as strong and masculine" that happens when both are perfectly healthy.
The relationship deteriorates. Not "the man just leaves".

video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
This was a great episode! However, this tagline not only fails to reflect the depth of this interview but also perpetuates harmful stereotypes about Black men. Connecting such a negative framing to Paul Brunson—a highly educated, respected, and thoughtful individual—reinforces damaging narratives that portray Black men as overly combative, confrontational, or lacking depth, which is the complete opposite of who Paul is and what he represents. As a branding expert, I understand the use of provocative marketing tactics, but this approach dishonors his brand and risks perpetuating biases that have long plagued media portrayals of Black men . Personally, I hesitated to watch the interview because of the tagline, and I know others who avoided it for the same reason. This is unfortunate because the conversation is filled with valuable insights that deserve a wider audience. A more thoughtful and respectful approach would have better served both Paul’s reputation and the integrity of DOAC. 

My two cents with love ❤

comment_text: People used to marry young, without need for college degrees and without major debt.  The couple would grow up together, learning life together.  They had friends and would have game nights and go to dances.  They had children young.  Their children grew up together and the moms helped each other.  The children could play outside while mom got stuff done inside (they were not hanging on her all day).  There was COMMUNITY.  We can criticize traditional living all we want...was it perfect, no.  But dang, people sure seemed happier than today.  And they had less money, less vacations, less modern conveniences.  Relationships between family and friends really made life worth living.  We want someone to make us happy but a single human being cannot replace community.  Your spouse cannot be your mother, your father, your best friend, your neighbor, your cousin, your aunt, your child.  No.  Your spouse is your spouse.  That is all.  Stop trying to make them be your community.

comment_text:
Amazingly with all that was discussed on this podcast, the outsized response to his comments about lowering standards for SOME things. Of course no one should accept abuse or dysfunction or toxicity in a relationship. But the height and money thing…as a woman i can see how that can be an unproductive thing on which to focus. 

Now i do agree (and from the perspective of a woman of means), that there are insecure men who just can’t handle that. I’ve been there and yes, THEY are NOT the answer lol.

But as I’ve listened to this pod, I thought to myself I’m currently in arguably the best relationship of my adult life…and i have no idea what his salary is lol. (And we’re going on two years lol!)

What I focused on instead that IS completely relevant is what he does with his money…does he save, does he live within his means, can he take me out occasionally, does he invest? The answer to all of those is yes. So I’m glad the question of his salary never came up and certainly that i never made that a prerequisite for a relationship.

Steven’s ideology on “marriage”, is 100% the same as mine. That being said, I do believe that marriage is for some people. I personally just think it’s important to be able to up and leave, if you find that the relationship is not growing at the same rate as you are. Some people accelerate at growth and some are more stagnant. It won’t work; and if you find someone that will grow with you, then you don’t need a piece of government paper to validate your commitment :)

I also believe that when you don’t sign that paper, it will give your partner a reason to continually work on the relationship, instead of becoming lazy and comfortable, within it. Just my opinion. I also believe that people should spend years on developing themselves (self growth), before they commit to another. You can’t possibly know what you want until you have discovered several layers about yourself. 

Idk 🤷🏻‍♀️ - I don’t think I’ll ever sign that paper, but I could be wrong. video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
I find the comments on this video interesting. I think a lot of people here are missing the nuance of the conversation and taking everything these men are saying at face value.

The biggest divide I’m seeing is the conversation about standards.

There’s a big difference between preference and standards. Standards are non negotiable, and everyone is entitled to have their standard. What you’re not entitled to is having unrealistic or unreasonable standards.

Preferences can be malleable. I could prefer a woman who is shorter than me, has a big butt, brunette hair, brown eyes and tan skin. But if I find a partner that meets my standards for what I need in a partner but doesn’t necessarily match all my preferences, then I’m willing to let those go in exchange for a wonderful partner and relationship.

This is where I think men and women have a fundamental difference.

comment_text: Do not let the sun go down on your wrath is also a biblical principle that is not necessarily understood and leads to the idea you should hammer out your problems before going to bed.  “Sleep on it” is also a common advice, too, however.  What I think is meant by the Bible verse, is to control your anger quickly, take a beat, go to bed before you do something rash or foolish in your anger.  Get emotionally regulated.  It doesn’t mean you have to resolve the issue that you are angry about before you go to bed.  And for sure it doesn’t mean stay up all night arguing until you do solve or dissolve.  The biblical verse does not say don’t go to bed angry, it says do not let the sun go down on your anger.  The biblical verse is telling you that one day is the reasonable limit to get yourself into wise mind, get control of your emotions, and acknowledge your wrath so you can then move on to make good, wise, high executive functions decisions about how you want to proceed to address the issue that provokes the anger.  So, semantics here, I would say you don’t go to bed angry, you control your reactions to your anger, so that you are not so emotionally dysregulated that  you can actually make the good decision to go to bed and “sleep on it”, and hopefully you won’t just pop off again the next day, but rather your anger can be intelligently channeled into peaceful resolution.

comment_text:
Keeping a long term relationship/marriage happy and healthy is the most difficult and nuanced things to understand and navigate. Ive been with my partner for 10 years. We have 2 kids, we both have ADHD, he comes from a broken violent home and mine was the exact opposite. My parents are still married and very supportive always.

We went through many rough patches, I seriously contemplated leaving multiple times. We have to remember that you don't throw something you love away just because its worn in and not brand new. People can't be replaced like a cell phone. Grass isn't always greener. The same communication problems and feelings will re-emerge over and over unless you learn how to handle them and self reflect. Nobody is 100% at fault in a car crash. We all have flaws and we can't blame others when they're not perfect. We're allowed to have bad days, that doesn't make us bad people. Forgiveness and honesty feeds the soul allows us to feel safe knowing we will still be loved despite our imperfections. 

Be teammates. Life is hard, work on game plans together so you both win! You both have strengths and weaknesses that benefit you both. Always acknowledge that & be self aware. Most importantly, their feelings are valid and so is their perspective whether you agree or not.

comment_text: I was a legal professional, college educated. My late husband was a truck driver. He was balding and overweight, wore cowboy boots and a Stetson hat. Do you know what attracted me to him? In addition to being funny and kind, he was impeccably dressed. I’m not talking about expensive clothes, but his jeans were clean, his shirt ironed, his boots polished. His old Dodge truck was always clean when he picked me up, he smelled good and he was well groomed. He put a napkin on his knee when he ate. He was popular at his work. People liked him! He was not racist nor spoke poorly of his ex. When we were married, I would wake up on Sunday mornings with him making pancakes with fresh strawberries, and there would be a rose on my pillow. When I was going through a tough time with my daughter and be upset, he would say ‘don’t worry darlin, my shoulders are big enough to carry both of our problems’. He would grab me and dance me around the kitchen. Unfortunately, he was killed in a work accident after only 13 years of marriage. He knew what it meant to be a man. I never found another one. He wasn’t rich, he didn’t work out, he didn’t have a sports car. He made me feel safe and supported emotionally. I hope I made him happy too. He was the love of my life. Take from this what you will.

comment_text: What a lovely tribute to your late husband and how happy a marriage you describe.  You've hit the nail on the head -- "he knew what it meant to be a man..." The truth is if you're looking for a partner to go the distance, a long-term relationship to last throughout the good times and the bad, you must marry someone with a strong foundation and good character.  Everything else can (and often will) fluctuate through the years - physical attraction, financial resources, etc. but a strong character never waivers. Sorry for your loss, you had a gem.

Male users between the ages of 20 and 50 found female users between the ages of 20 and 24 most attractive. Women found men a few years older than themselves most attractive, but after 40 they found younger men attractive. In reality, 40-year-old men and 50-year-old men sent the most messages to 30-year-old and 40-year-old women, respectively. video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
@TheOlzee  Not necessarily. I believe gf/bf status is a necessary step. But I believe if 2 people are in a relationship and one wants marriage and the other doesn't, at some point, there must be a compromise. 
What I've noticed and experienced is that a man or even a woman will say, "I don't believe in marriage" or "I don't want to get married," or "I don't want kids," but many of these same people will break their own boundaries with someone they're head over heels for or who they believe is worth it. 
If I am in love and believe I'm with the person I want to be with for the rest of my life, I will commit. If commitment looks like marriage for my partner, because a relationship is about compromise, I will consider that. If my reasons are, "they could take my money in the future," "they could leave me in the future," overall, just being afraid of the future "what-ifs,"  "unknowns" or "failures," than I'm choosing to focus on the negative, and allow that to deter me from the possibility of feeling fully satisfied in my relationship with the person I truly love. Because if your partner wants marriage and you don't,  then there's dissatisfaction in the relationship already. 
I understand that everyone has different views and values, and I might not be considering other "possible" reasons that could be valid from my pov, but that is yet to be determined, lol. 
Men/Women who do not commit to marriage most times it's because they are afraid of losing something and they're not willing to put it all on the line for love (most times because they aren't ready or they don't feel strongly enough for the person they are with). Of course, you can live and love a bf/gf til death do you part, and I get that some people are logical and scientific, and they lead less with emotion, but there's an emotional part to being human, that I strongly believe must be acknowledged and fed. The majority of women want to KNOW that their person, their true love, will risk it all for the sake of loving them. We're not asking men to do anything criminal or irrational. We just want you to say, "I love you enough to go there with you because I DO (pun) love you and you're more important to me than the fears, the unknowns and the risks". 

To simplify it. If you're bf/gf, there's no risk in saying you love someone. You break up, you go your separate way, there's no mountain to descend, there's nothing. To us, that means "you're not worthy enough for me to risk it all for." Period.

comment_text:
Mathematically infeasible and false.  It's objectively money and social status, the overwhelming majority of women will not marry a man who earns less than them.  Women typically will also not marry a man who they consider socially "below" them either, ie a plumber might make more than a woman, but because he's not "educated" nor does he have a high social status, an "educated" women won't consider him her equal.    Women are naturally hypergamous, that's an evolutionary reality that's backed by numerous studies across nearly all cultures.  In a society where women and men are social and economic equals, there will always been a debt of "marriageable men" because women don't marry down, only men marry down... that's just basic math.  It has nothing to do with "respect, emotional availability or, sharing of the domestic load".  That's completely illogical nonsense.  Modern western men are more respectful, emotional available, and willing to share the domestic load than at any time in history, and yet this wasn't a problem before modern history and dating apps... even as recently as ~20-30 years ago.

The real reason is two fold, women's social and economic status has risen to the point where there are not mathematically more men above than than below them as was historically the case, and social media and dating apps have driven women's hypergamous nature into overdrive by giving them a daily dose of seemingly "better" options delivered write to the palm of your hand.  What it's essentially created is a large group of women sharing only a handful of the men who meet their increasingly high standards.  You've essentially turned yourselves into an online harem and then wonder why these men won't commit to you.

video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
You don't understand. The point is that you shouldn't be looking for everything in one person. When you're looking for someone who can do 3 things instead of 10, you might actually find someone of superior ability in those 3 areas. Not only you're lowering your chances if you do look for everything in one person, that person is going to be bigger compromise (you will have to use a lower standard to find anyone at all).

Say, only my partner can be a mother to my children. So, being a good mother is a high priority. But anyone can go mountaineering with me. I can easily find someone for intellectual debates. I don't even have to do it in person, we can be pen pals. Realize what is the core and what is just a bonus. And be grateful when you find someone who fits your core needs well. PS: Let's go back to intellect. She needs to be smart enough that I don't look down at her. I can't date an airhead. But she doesn't have to be so smart that I admire her for her intellect. Because there is plethora of things I can admire her for. And the biggie is being a good mother, that really works for me (it just tickles the right button in my brain). Even though I would love to have philosophical debates with my partner, it's not necessary. Everyone likes a pretty face but the fact is that brain filters out constant stimuli - you get used to her face and you stop perceiving it. I even have a theory that imperfections serve in bonding (perhaps a better way of putting it would be features that stand out). Because imperfections make us individual.

Otherwise, if you do insist on ticking all the boxes, you might be unhappy with a partner that is actually a very good fit for you just because he doesn't fit some irrelevant, BS box that you think you need which could easily be ticked elsewhere. Being happy and content is in a way skill. Some people are just determined to be miserable. A big factor is the ability to set expectations. High expectations are always a recipe for dissatisfaction. That's just the way it is. That's why it's important to cut it down to the bone, to determine what really matters and throw the rest out.

If you want a committed relationship, that puts unique demands on it. And you should prioritize corresponding qualities. If I fall out with a friend, I can easily find someone else to go mountaineering with. There is no long-term commitment. And in a way, it makes it easier. Non-committed relationships are easier to navigate, easier to be happy with. You need particular skills for a committed relationship. And not all people are cut out for it.

comment_text:
Okay I was really giving this the benefit of the doubt to see what he says. I have a problem with how he structures his argument around why men leave a terminally ill partner 21% of the time, while women leave a terminally ill partner roughly 3% of the time. His argument can be broken down into 3 basic premises: 
p1- Love is conditional for satisfactory romantic relationships
p2. People experiencing a low satisfaction relationship are more likely to leave when the going gets tough (like financial stress, or partner illness) 
p3. When a partner falls ill the sick partner can no longer fulfill the conditions the caretaking partner needs to feel satisfied in the relationship. 
C1. Therefore, people leave unsatisfactory relationships because their ill partner is no longer fulfilling their needs. 

The problem is, that argument doesn't explain why men leave almost a quarter of the time while women are more likely to say. If it were logically consistent, then either women would also leave 20% of the time or men would leave 3% of the time.  It provides no insight as to why. I think we can *infer* why, but that's what we get for listening to a business major talk about psycho-social interactions.

Attachment styles, like anxious or avoidant, influence relationship dynamics; self-awareness and personal well-being are crucial.

Strong relationships, married or not, impact personal happiness and health, underscoring the importance of autonomy and partnership needs.

Myths like resolving conflicts before sleep and the finality of infidelity are challenged, advocating for rational conflict resolution and openness.

Jealousy and digital infidelity require constructive communication and personal growth efforts to enhance trust and satisfaction.

video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text:
Basing an important life decision upon one’s likelihood of ‘possibly feeling different or wanting variety later’ seems like a recipe for failure. Of course we all change. We ARE free to walk away from a partner, good, bad or indifferent, affecting offspring or not.

I’m not trying to reengineer this video after it was made, but when a person refuses to contemplate long-term commitment, it’s on them, not about their litany of excuses or projections. It’s also IMO a weak move to speculate about the infinite ways we could be betrayed or disappointed.

I say if one partner views another as lesser/not trustworthy, it reflects upon them just as much. Taking full responsibility seems like territory for heroes in times when the hero types we see feted as the best examples turn out to be equally human on various levels. But what do we expect? Superheroes on demand while expecting nothing but consumerism from ourselves?

I’ve had similar experiences. When jealousy and resentment exist in a relationship, they often indicate what Paul Brunson classifies as "too much expectation." Our past partners expected to always be superior to us without making the effort required to actually achieve that superiority. As a result, they became resentful, often making nasty remarks or even becoming violent. They lacked the capacity to process their emotions in a healthy way and instead channeled their frustration into a desire to bring us down rather than striving to reach the same level. In doing so, they expected their partners—us at the time—to diminish our personalities and success just to make them feel better about themselves.

I don’t think Brunson is referring to expectation in the sense of expecting a compatible and emotionally mature partner. Instead, I believe he’s talking about the unrealistic expectations we place on our partners to meet all our needs.

This conversation is multifaceted.

Women, if you make a man feel inadequate, whether intentionally or unintentionally, then just like any other self-respecting human, he will lose interest. Just like women who cant date men who are more attractive physically or in-shape than they are—It brings up insecurities. 

However, those insecurities are the problem of the insecure person—in this case the man. But ladies, let’s not pretend that men are the talkative type or the type to bring up their feelings about feeling emasculated or anything less than adequate. Men have a lot of pride and quite frankly it is because they are expected to be supermen when it comes to everything they touch. But that feeling comes from other men *as well as women*. Values are e.g. the acceptance of the scientific method, of rational reasoning, growth, life, there exists an objective reality, good, evil.

One doesn’t have to share the same beliefs, because if one shares the right values, one can find the truth, examine beliefs together, learn, and grow.

Someone who doesn’t share my fundamental values can never accept me fully, and acceptance is key to any lasting relationship.

video_title: Paul Brunson: Women Need To Lower Their Standards! If They Have These 3 Traits, Never Let Them Go!
comment_text: I call it the Swiss Army knife effect. Yes you can have one for everything, but it won’t last as long as having a full set of tools at your disposal. No matter how well made it is. Requiring your partner to fit all the roles of a “village” has the same effect. It wears out/down faster, and is never as good as having a full social circle to bounce off of. You see this with children too. A lot of parents say it’s easier to have more children because they take care of, and play with each other. So it can be more effort to just have one, because the parent has to spend more time with the child filling that gap left by a lack of siblings of socialisation/play time. It’s not just a dating problem it’s a cultural problem, in an increasingly individualistic society. There has to be a tipping point where there is not enough culture left to individuate from.  So it all falls apart. That, along with the internet creating an echo chamber for absolutely anything you believe to be true, full of terrible advice, with no lasting ramifications, since it’s from strangers. A person you live with day to day will always give you better advice.

DOAC video request: How Can Anyone Be a Genuine Feminist If You’re Drinking Milk and Eating Eggs?

The denial of animal rights originates in the same supremacist thinking that has obstructed women’s rights. Some are quick to dismiss the suffering of females of other species as unimportant, but females – regardless of species – are the victims of systematic oppression.

Humans’ justifications for discounting other animals’ suffering and denying their basic rights are based on speciesism and are strikingly similar to those that have been used to disregard women’s suffering and disallow them their fundamental rights.

Being violated without consent isn’t just a human problem. Animal agriculture is entirely reliant on female exploitation. On farms, female animals are confined, forcibly impregnated, and killed so their ovulation markers, milk, and other body parts can be sold for human consumption.

Cows are wonderful mothers who, just like humans, carry their babies for nine months and nurse them, developing a strong bond.

Cows make milk for the same reason women do: to feed their babies. They produce milk only when they’re pregnant or nursing. On dairy farms, they are repeatedly forcibly impregnated through artificial insemination while being restrained in a contraption the industry calls a “rape rack”. In commercial dairy farming, their babies are taken from them within 24 hours of birth, and if they are female, they will enter the same cycle of misery as their mother. The male calves are killed or sold into the veal industry.

Mother cows often bellow and call out frantically for their young for several days or weeks after they’ve been torn from them.

The strain of continual pregnancy exhausts cows and often leaves them emaciated, with mastitis (infected udders), or lame. When they are worn out and can no longer produce high volumes of milk, they are sent to the abattoir and killed.

Farmers treat hens like egg-laying machines. They use light and food to manipulate their reproductive systems to induce extra laying cycles, forcing them to produce as many as 300 eggs per year – far more than the 10 to 15 their ancestors produced in nature.

Because of this, they often suffer from cysts, infections, ovarian carcinomas, and reproductive tumours and sometimes multiple eggs become lodged inside them – which is life-threatening. Their bones often shatter from osteoporosis because their bodies are forced to produce unnaturally high quantities of eggshells, day after day, without rest.

When their egg production begins to wane, these sensitive animals are shoved into cramped crates and endure a harrowing journey to the abattoir. Over a million chickens die in transit each year in the UK. Those who survive the journey are shackled by their legs before their throats are cut – sometimes while they’re still conscious.
